english:
  title: Elegy for Choe Sung-je, the Esteemed Minister
  author: Choe Ja
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Though he rose to minister with raven hair in the Purple Secretariat,
    Yet grieved that his rank never reached the highest pinnacle.
    What fame can the weighty name of Samhan bestow?
    His towering steps through ages—how difficult to follow.
    The red cinnamon plucked in his hand returns to the moon,
    The green pine in his breast cannot endure the winter.
    Virtue's star and letters' star have both scattered and dissolved—
    Who now will ride together on those twin constellations?
  footnotes:
    - The Purple Secretariat (紫樞) refers to the highest governmental office, while 'raven hair' is a classical expression for youth and vitality, suggesting his rise to power in his prime.
    - Samhan (三韓) refers to the Three Kingdoms period of Korean history, invoking the weight of historical legacy.
    - The cinnamon and pine are traditional symbols of virtue and steadfastness in Chinese poetry; their inability to endure suggests the fragility of human achievement.
    - The final image of twin stars references Confucian ideals of virtue and literary accomplishment, suggesting the departure of an exemplary figure.
